# Cerebro — Database & Infrastructure Rules

> Always reference @docs/data-schema.md for the full schema definition, all enums, mock data, and document registry before writing any database code.
> Always reference @docs/architecture.md for the VaultService access control pattern.

## Prisma Rules

### Schema
- The canonical schema lives in @docs/data-schema.md — always sync `prisma/schema.prisma` against it
- Never add a column or table without updating `data-schema.md` first
- All string IDs use `@default(cuid())` — never auto-increment integers for entity IDs
- All tables have `createdAt DateTime @default(now())` 
- Tables that are updated have `updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt`
- The `AgentAction` table is append-only — never add an `updatedAt` to it
- Index every foreign key column and every column used in WHERE clauses

### Migrations
- Always run `npx prisma migrate dev --name [descriptive-name]` — never edit migration files manually
- Migration names describe what changed: `add-document-notification-count` not `update-schema`
- Never run `prisma db push` in production — always use migrations

### Prisma Client
- The Prisma client singleton lives in `src/lib/db/client.ts` only
- Import the prisma client as: `import { prisma } from "@/lib/db/client"`
- Never instantiate `new PrismaClient()` anywhere except `src/lib/db/client.ts`
- Use the standard Next.js singleton pattern to prevent hot-reload connection pool exhaustion

```typescript
// src/lib/db/client.ts — this is the only correct pattern
import { PrismaClient } from "@prisma/client"

const globalForPrisma = globalThis as unknown as { prisma: PrismaClient }

export const prisma = globalForPrisma.prisma ?? new PrismaClient({
  log: process.env.NODE_ENV === "development" ? ["query", "error"] : ["error"],
})

if (process.env.NODE_ENV !== "production") globalForPrisma.prisma = prisma
```

## VaultService Rules

### The Core Pattern
VaultService is the ONLY way agents and tools access the database. This is non-negotiable.

```typescript
// CORRECT — always build VaultService first, pass it to tools
const vault = new VaultService({ clientId: "CLT-001" })
const tools = buildComplianceTools(vault)

// WRONG — never do this
const docs = await prisma.document.findMany({ where: { clientId } })
```

### VaultService Methods
- Every method on VaultService is scoped to `this.clientId` — no exceptions
- No VaultService method accepts a `clientId` parameter — it uses `this.clientId` exclusively
- Read methods never write — write methods always call `logAction` as part of their operation
- If a new data access pattern is needed, add a method to VaultService — never bypass it

### Action Log Rules
- `AgentAction` records are insert-only — never update or delete them
- Every action log entry must have a non-empty `reasoning` string — enforce this at the VaultService level with a runtime check
- `nextScheduledAt` must always be set on action records — use `addDays(new Date(env.DEMO_DATE), N)` 
- The `trigger` field must always reflect how the agent run was initiated: `SCHEDULED`, `EVENT_UPLOAD`, `MANUAL`, or `SIMULATION`

## Seed Script Rules

### Idempotency
- The seed script must be fully idempotent — running it twice produces identical results
- Use `upsert` with the mock ID as the unique key for all seed records
- Never use `create` in the seed script — always `upsert`
- Print a summary at the end: how many records were created vs. already existed

### DEMO_DATE
- All document expiry dates in the seed script are computed as offsets from `env.DEMO_DATE`
- Use `addDays(new Date(env.DEMO_DATE), offset)` where offset is the number from @docs/data-schema.md
- Never hardcode a real calendar date in the seed script
- Positive offset = future date, negative offset = past date

### Seed Order
Always seed in this order to satisfy foreign key constraints:
1. Firms
2. Advisors (compliance officers first, then advisors)
3. Update firms with `complianceOfficerId`
4. Clients
5. Documents (all statuses per the table in data-schema.md)
6. Pre-populated AgentAction records (CLT-003, CLT-011 history)

### Demo Reset Script
`scripts/reset-demo.ts` must:
- Delete all `AgentAction` records except pre-populated history
- Reset all `Document` statuses to their initial seed state
- Reset all `Client.onboardingStage` to seed values
- Re-run the seed upserts
- Complete in under 30 seconds
- Be safe to run at any time without data loss risk

## Enum Rules

- All enum values in application code come from `src/lib/db/enums.ts` — never use raw strings
- Prisma enums and TypeScript enums must stay in sync — update both when adding values
- Use `as const` objects in TypeScript, not `enum` keyword — avoids transpilation issues

```typescript
// CORRECT
import { DocumentStatus } from "@/lib/db/enums"
if (doc.status === DocumentStatus.EXPIRED) { ... }

// WRONG
if (doc.status === "EXPIRED") { ... }
```

## BullMQ / Queue Rules

### Queue Separation
Three queues — never mix their job types:
- `cerebro-priority` — event-driven document uploads, manual dashboard triggers
- `cerebro-scheduled` — cron-based full vault scans
- `cerebro-simulation` — simulation batch jobs only

Simulation jobs never go into priority or scheduled queues. Live agent jobs never go into the simulation queue.

### Job Payload Types
Every queue job has a strongly typed payload defined in `src/lib/queue/jobs.ts`:

```typescript
// src/lib/queue/jobs.ts
export type AgentJobPayload = {
  clientId:   string
  agentType:  "COMPLIANCE" | "ONBOARDING"
  trigger:    "SCHEDULED" | "EVENT_UPLOAD" | "MANUAL"
  documentId?: string   // only present for EVENT_UPLOAD trigger
}

export type SimulationJobPayload = {
  runId:     string
  batchStart: number
  batchEnd:   number
}
```

Never enqueue a job without the correct typed payload — validate with Zod before enqueuing.

### Worker Concurrency
- `cerebro-priority` worker: concurrency 5
- `cerebro-scheduled` worker: concurrency 3
- `cerebro-simulation` worker: concurrency 10 (mock agent, no LLM calls)
- Rate limiter: 20 agent jobs per second across all live queues — respects OpenRouter limits

### Job Retry Configuration
```typescript
// Standard retry config — use for all live agent jobs
defaultJobOptions: {
  attempts: 3,
  backoff: { type: "exponential", delay: 2000 },
  removeOnComplete: { count: 1000 },
  removeOnFail: { count: 500 },
}
```

### Upstash Redis Connection
```typescript
// CORRECT — use this pattern for Vercel serverless compatibility
const connection = new IORedis(env.UPSTASH_REDIS_URL, {
  maxRetriesPerRequest: null,  // required for BullMQ
  tls: { rejectUnauthorized: false },
})

// WRONG — standard Redis won't work on Vercel serverless
const connection = new IORedis(env.REDIS_URL)
```

## Supabase Realtime Rules

### Channel Naming
- Agent actions channel: `"cerebro-agent-actions"`
- Simulation progress channel: `"cerebro-simulation-[runId]"`
- Never use generic names like `"changes"` or `"updates"`

### Subscription Cleanup
- Always store the subscription reference and call `.unsubscribe()` on component unmount
- Use the `useEffect` cleanup function in React components — never leave dangling subscriptions

### What Gets Published
- Only `INSERT` events on `agent_actions` table go to the dashboard feed
- Only `UPDATE` events on `simulation_runs` table go to simulation progress
- Never subscribe to full table scans — always filter by specific event type and table
